cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "Architectural Observability Collapse in Transformers"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it using the metadata from this file."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: Carmichael
    given-names: Thomas
version: "4.0.1"
date-released: "2026-05-05"
license: MIT
doi: "10.5281/zenodo.19435674"
repository-code: "https://github.com/tmcarmichael/nn-observability"
abstract: "Autoregressive transformers make confident errors, but activation monitoring can catch them only if training preserves an internal decision-quality signal that output confidence does not expose. Monitorability is an architectural property before it is a monitor-design problem. We measure this via observability: the linear readability of per-token decision quality from frozen mid-layer activations after controlling for max-softmax confidence and activation norm. Confidence controls absorb on average 60.3% of raw probe signal across 14 models in 6 families. Observability is not a generic property of transformers. In Pythia's controlled suite, every tested run with the 24-layer, 16-head configuration collapses to pcorr approximately 0.10 across a 3.5x parameter gap and two Pile variants, while six other configurations occupy a separated healthy band from 0.21 to 0.38. The output-controlled residual collapses at the same points, and neither tested nonlinear probes nor layer sweeps recover healthy-range signal. Checkpoint dynamics show the collapse is emergent during training. At matched hidden dimension, both 1B and 1.4B form the signal at the earliest measured checkpoint. Training erases the signal in 1.4B even as it reaches lower final loss than 1B. Across independent recipes the collapse map changes but the phenomenon persists. Qwen 2.5 and Llama differ by 2.9x at matched 3B scale with probe seed distributions that do not overlap, while Mistral 7B v0.3 preserves observability where Llama 3.1 8B collapses despite similar broad architecture. Within Qwen 2.5, observability persists from 0.5B through 32B. A WikiText-trained observer transfers to downstream QA without training on those tasks, catching errors confidence misses. At 20% flag rate, exclusive catch reaches 10.9-13.4% of all errors on most downstream model-task cells, near the 12-15% language-modeling ceiling. Architecture selection is a monitoring decision."
keywords:
  - neural network observability
  - transformer interpretability
  - decision quality
  - learned probes
  - confidence controls
  - architecture-dependent readability
  - partial correlation
  - cross-family evaluation
  - downstream QA transfer
